This is the default rule for normal product names (single-word or non-generic multi-word) that are not of the “specific + generic tail” type described below.

2) Compound product phrases with a generic tail
(reference pattern: “chilli powder”)

Some product names are compound phrases where the first word is specific and the second word is very generic (e.g., “chilli powder”, “garlic powder”, “turmeric powder”). For these, you MUST treat the specific word as the anchor and MUST NOT rely on the generic tail alone.

When the user explicitly mentions such a compound phrase (for example, “chilli powder”):

Conceptually, the product_description filter MUST require:

the anchor word (e.g., “chilli”), and

the generic descriptor (e.g., “powder”),

both being effectively present, with an optional fuzzy backup for misspellings of the whole phrase.

This pattern OVERRIDES the default “contains ⇒ trigram %” behavior on product_description only for that compound phrase. For normal single-word / non-generic names, use the standard rule above.

For the reference phrase “chilli powder”, the SQL condition in the Implementation Plan and Generated SQL MUST be logically equivalent to:

AND (
  (UPPER(product_description) LIKE '%CHILL%' 
   AND UPPER(product_description) LIKE '%POWDER%')
  OR word_similarity(UPPER(product_description), 'CHILLI POWDER') > 0.7
)

Where:

The LIKE conditions enforce that both the anchor and the generic descriptor appear in the description
(e.g., “RED CHILLI POWDER”, “EXTRA HOT CHILLI POWDER”).

The similarity(…, 'CHILLI POWDER') > 0.7 condition is a tight fuzzy backup to catch small misspellings of the full phrase
(e.g., “CHILI POWDER”, “CHILLY POWDER”) without admitting unrelated powders.

When adapting this pattern to other compound phrases:

Replace CHILL with the stem/anchor of the specific word (e.g., GARLIC, TURMERIC).

Replace POWDER with the appropriate generic tail if applicable (e.g., OIL, PASTE), but only when the phrase clearly has that “specific + generic” structure.

Replace 'CHILLI POWDER' inside similarity(...) with the full phrase for that product (e.g., 'GARLIC POWDER').

You MUST NOT:

Use the generic tail alone as a filter (e.g., filter just by “POWDER” for “chilli powder”).

Return rows where product_description matches or is similar to the generic tail but not the anchor word
(e.g., “MILK POWDER”, “DETERGENT POWDER”, “BATH POWDER” must be excluded for the “chilli powder” case).

Broaden the filter to all generic products unless the anchor word (or its close misspelling captured by similarity(...) > 0.7) is also effectively present.

This “compound phrase” rule is a reference pattern: whenever you encounter similar “specific + generic” product phrases in user queries, you MUST follow this structure (anchor + generic via LIKE, plus a high-threshold similarity(...) on the full phrase) instead of treating the generic term alone as the product.

